  <tbody>
  <tr>
  <td>Cat hair on everything — couch, clothes, counter<br><span style="font-size:.8rem;color:var(--muted-foreground);">Loose undercoat fur never gets removed before it sheds naturally</span></td>
  <td>Silicone bristles pull out dead fur in the brush, not on your couch<br><span style="font-size:.8rem;color:var(--muted-foreground);">One 10-minute session removes a surprising amount before it detaches</span></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
  <td>Weekly hairballs despite regular grooming<br><span style="font-size:.8rem;color:var(--muted-foreground);">Cat self-grooms constantly, swallowing loose fur that builds into hairballs</span></td>
  <td>Steam loosens undercoat; massage relaxes cat for longer sessions<br><span style="font-size:.8rem;color:var(--muted-foreground);">Less loose fur in coat = less fur ingested = fewer hairballs</span></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
  <td>Cat tolerates brushing 2 minutes then bolts<br><span style="font-size:.8rem;color:var(--muted-foreground);">Metal tines create discomfort, especially near spine and haunches</span></td>
  <td>Soft silicone + warm steam = gentler contact; cats tolerate longer<br><span style="font-size:.8rem;color:var(--muted-foreground);">Massage motion mimics licking, which cats find calming</span></td>
  </tr>
  </tbody>
  </table>
