  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq supporting-questions">
  <div class="faq-item"><h3>Will this brush hurt my cat's skin or damage their undercoat?</h3><p>No — the soft silicone bristles flex against the skin rather than scraping. Unlike metal deshedding tools, there are no hard tines that can cut or break guard hairs. The steam function helps loosen fur before the bristles touch skin.</p></div>
  <div class="faq-item"><h3>How often should I brush my cat with a deshedding tool?</h3><p>3-4 times per week is ideal for most indoor cats. Daily is fine and reduces hairballs most effectively. Short sessions (5-10 minutes) are better than infrequent long ones.</p></div>
  <div class="faq-item"><h3>Is the steam function actually helpful or just hype?</h3><p>It helps. Steam loosens undercoat making bristles more effective per stroke. Many cats find the warm mist calming, which extends grooming time. It's not a substitute for thorough brushing on heavy shedders.</p></div>
  <div class="faq-item"><h3>Will this work if my cat hates being brushed?</h3><p>Better than metal alternatives. The silicone + steam combination is gentler. Cats that bolt from a Furminator often tolerate this brush 2-3x longer. Introduce it slowly with treats and short sessions.</p></div>
  <div class="faq-item"><h3>How does this compare to a Furminator?</h3><p>The Furminator uses steel tines that go deeper into the undercoat — more effective on thick-coated breeds but risks guard hair damage with overuse. This brush is gentler and better for daily use on average-coat cats.</p></div>
  <div class="faq-item"><h3>Is it easy to clean after use?</h3><p>Yes. Fur sits on top of silicone bristles and peels off in one motion. Rinse the brush head under warm water — done in under 30 seconds. The reservoir unscrews for separate cleaning.</p></div>
  <div class="faq-item"><h3>Is this water-resistant or completely waterproof?</h3><p>The brush handle is water-resistant but not fully waterproof. The motor housing repels water from regular rinsing, but do not submerge the entire brush or spray directly into the motor vents. Empty the water reservoir after each use and allow it to air dry.</p></div>
  <div class="faq-item"><h3>How long does the water reservoir last per grooming session?</h3><p>The reservoir holds enough water for approximately 10-15 minutes of continuous steam production. For most grooming sessions (5-10 minutes), one fill is sufficient. Refill between cats or for longer sessions.</p></div>
  <div class="faq-item"><h3>What type of water should I use - filtered, distilled, or tap?</h3><p>Distilled water is recommended to prevent mineral buildup in the steam nozzles. Tap water works fine but may leave residue over time. Avoid very hard water areas if possible. Clean the nozzles monthly with a soft brush if you notice reduced steam output.</p></div>
  <div class="faq-item"><h3>Does this work on long-haired cats or only short-haired breeds?</h3><p>It works on both, but is most effective on medium to long-haired cats. For very long, matted coats, you may need to make multiple passes or use a detangling spray first. The steam is especially helpful for long-haired breeds because it separates mats before brushing.</p></div>
